replies.text:
@montec6113 Assuming you have a surface plate, you can measure flatness (to tolerances as per the plate).  You can also measure squareness, to within the tolerances of your squareness measuring tools.  You can generate squares using the same techniques as generating flat plates, but you can also make a "square" from a cylinder - many reference squares are, in fact, cylindrical, and if we assume the cylinder you wish to verify comes from a lathe and has ends that can be used as a flat base, you can control cylindricity to some extent by controlling the squareness of the sides WRT their end, directly on the surface plate.

That doesn't control the rotational accuracy, though, so you measure parallelism versus the surface plate itself.  For some setups, particularly bores,  this will require some clever fixturing.

back to the original point, though, here's a concrete example.  I've made a spherometer, which is capable of measuring sphericity via displacements of a measuring point at a sub-micron level.  It's a very crude instrument, made from a chunk of cast iron, turned pretty roughly to no particular tolerance, with 4 drilled (on a shagged out 1980s chinese drill press) and tapped by hand, 4 M5 bolts of no particular merit with 3.8mm bearings let into the ends, and a graduated scale.  It works splendidly.
